text: At first glance, the complex intersection of Rossdale Road, Bellamy Hill Road, and 103 Street looks like a nightmare, but it allows the safe flow of vehicles and pedestrians even during high traffic as users cross in phases. Starting Monday, June 19, this intersection will become simpler as Edmonton City Council has decided to close access from Rossdale Road westbound, which also eliminates the beautifully designed free flowing road infrastructure connecting traffic from Grierson Hill and McDougall Hill. Instead, vehicles will be diverted to 99 Ave to access Bellamy Hill Road where a new traffic light has been added. I will miss my shortcut from Connors Road via Low Level Bridge towards 109 Street as this was actually faster than using the James Macdonald Bridge turn off due to multiple traffic light phases along 98 Ave, but I do understand that this intersection may be overwhelming to some drivers.

text: Galápagos penguins are endangered, with an estimate of fewer than 2,000 individuals remaining. A new study using model predictions has uncovered a likely rapid accumulation of microplastics across the food web, with the most microplastics building up in the endangered penguins, then moving down the food web to barracuda, anchovies, sardines, herrings, black-striped salema, and zooplankton. “The goal of this food web bioaccumulation modeling work was to provide science and data to support risk management of hazardous plastic waste, reduce microplastic emissions in the oceans and marine remote UNESCO Heritage sites such as the Galápagos Islands, and inform local and international marine policy to conserve endangered, endemic seabird species of Galápagos Marine Reserve,” Juan Jose Alava, senior author of the study and principal investigator of the Ocean Pollution Research Unit at the University of British Columbia’s Institute for the Oceans and Fisheries Full article below https://www.ecowatch.com/microplastics-galapagos-penguins.html

text: The Kampala Flyover Road Project is a road-improvement initiative in the Central Division of Kampala, the capital city of Uganda. Here are the key details: Objective: The project aims to decongest the city by separating through-traffic from city-street traffic. It focuses on traffic entering the city, mainly from Entebbe along the old Kampala-Entebbe Road and from Mpigi along the Kampala-Mpigi Expressway. Construction: The project involves constructing flyovers at the “Clock Tower” and “Kitgum House,” widening Nsambya Road and Mukwano Road, and improving interfacing roads and junctions. The project stretches over approximately 3.5 kilometers (2 miles). Funding: The Ugandan government, with financing from the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA), funds the project. Progress: Despite challenges posed by the COVID-19 outbreak, construction is progressing steadily. Excavation works on the 4-lane underpass are nearing completion, and screw piles for the flyover and pedestrian bridges have been delivered on-site12. This project aims to enhance urban transportation, reduce travel times, and alleviate traffic congestion in Kampala. 🚗 #ugandanstiktok #kampalaflyover

text: Ever wondered how some people can seemingly defy the laws of nature by dipping their hands into boiling oil without getting burned? Meet the Leidenfrost effect – a remarkable physical phenomenon where a protective vapor layer is formed due to intense heat, momentarily insulating the skin from the scorching temperature. This fleeting barrier is created when the moisture on the skin instantly vaporizes upon contact with the hot oil. While this might look like a superhuman feat, it’s a dangerous and fleeting trick relying more on physics than on fearlessness. Remember, don’t try this at home – understanding the science is cool, but safety always comes first! #leidenfrosteffect #medical #culinary #science #viral

text: Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez paid tribute to the late #Pose Actress Cecilia Gentili. Cecilia Gentili, an Argentina-born artist and activist known for her work in the immigrant and transgender rights movements in New York City, is being widely remembered following her death last week. She was 52. As an actress, Gentili stood out with her memorable portrayal of Ms. Orlando on the groundbreaking series Pose, which illuminated the experiences of trans women of colour during the AIDS crisis of the 1980s. News of her death broke on Tuesday (February 6), when close friends and family took to her Instagram page to announce her passing, saying: “Our beloved Cecilia Gentili passed away this morning to continue watching over us in spirit. Please be gentle with each other and love one another with ferocity.” Gentili was seen by many as a symbol of hope and resilience. Her journey from Argentina to the bustling streets of New York City was marked by her continuing unwavering advocacy for marginalised communities, from undocumented immigrants to sex workers. She took pivotal roles at prominent organisations like New York City–based AIDS non-profit GMHC and founded Trans Equity Consulting, where her mission was to amplify the voices of marginalised communities. Her activism also took the form of initiatives like Transmissions Fest, a music festival aimed at putting transgender voices centre stage, and fundraising event Fierce Futures in support of Black trans people. Tributes to Cecilia poured in across social media from a range of people from all walks of life. American writer and book editor Raquel Willis said: “Cecilia Gentili was a living legend. A titan, an unapologetic example of trans joy and power. Her spirit lives on in all whom she touched and all she built for us. Rest powerfully and peacefully, Mami. And go kiki with the ancestors. You deserve eternal pleasure.” All of the tributes made one thing very clear: that Cecilia Gentili’s impact had transcended boundaries and will linger for decades to come. #ceciliagentili #trans #lgbt #aoc #uspolitics

text: An inventor from Piedmont, CA noticed that cars were getting larger, while parking spots continued to shrink. He invented the “Park-Car,” which was a car that utilized the spare tire in order to make more abrupt turns and aid in parallel parking. The tire drops down from the trunk of the car, lifting the back two tires off the ground, and acts as a swivel rotating or spinning the back of the car out of any tight spot. This invention utilized a car’s spare tire as a 5th wheel helping in parking. It may look funny and eventually failed, but was very effective. Like our content? Follow 👉 @intels for more

text: It's no secret some San Francisco businesses have been hit hard by rampant theft and shoplifting. Safeway has installed gates inside some of their high-theft San Francisco stores where customers have to scan their receipts to exit. At least two San Francisco Safeway stores have the new sliding gates, including this one on Webster Street and the Mission Street store in the Excelsior District. A Safeway spokeswoman wrote in a statement to KPIX 5, "recent changes were made at select Safeway stores in the Bay Area... given the increasing amount of theft. Those updates include operational changes to the front end of the stores to deter shoplifting." Safeway has tried many security measures in recent years, including metal gates to prevent people from leaving through closed registers and long metal poles attached to shopping carts so people can't just run out with a cart full of products. #sanfrancisco #sf #bayarea #california #safeway #shopping #store #groceries #news

text: The moon, seen from the Arctic Circle, between Russia and Canada. It only lasts a few seconds, but it's worth seeing.  It's a spectacular sight.  Imagine that you are in a location between Canada and Russia and suddenly and for just 30 seconds, the moon appears in all its splendor and disappears before your eyes.   It looks like the moon is going to collide with the earth.   Even more impressive AND for just 5 seconds, a total eclipse of the sun takes place.   It's unprecedented and spectacular!     The video was shot in REAL-TIME. The phenomenon happens at the “perigee”:  the closest point of a heavenly body’s orbit around the Earth, where the proximity of the moon is so evident that, suddenly, we realize the great speed at which the Earth is moving.  This effect is only visible once a year and lasts for just 30 seconds… Astronomers figured out those exact 30 seconds and had the cameras rolling.  Fortunately they had a clear sky.  Amazing!  Watch this happen on the video. Total sun eclipse is ONLY 5 seconds….   #Space #Moon #Eclipse

text: Extremely rare white African wild dog puppy 4 Rivers is currently home to an extraordinary pack of wild dogs with a very leucistic pup. Local researchers have confirmed that this is extremely rare and virtually unheard of in Botswana for the past 30 years or so 🐾 In the 1990s, guides first spotted leucistic puppies in the Kwando area. The males of Kwando's pack have dispersed. These men, identified by photos, established a group dubbed the Golden Pack in the Vumbura area. Some descendants of this golden pack started another family in Kwara, where leucism was still evident but somewhat diluted. Leucism tends to be a lack of melanin in the skin, feathers, or hair. Melanin is the natural pigment responsible for most brown and black coloring. It is mostly genetic and varies in degree, going all the way to pure white in rare cases (like this one at 4 Rivers) or like in the "golden" Vumbura dogs, which are a pale tan tone. Currently, the pup interacts normally with its siblings and adult painted wolves (as African wild dogs are also known). Although this little one is anything but painted! If anything, it's dominant in the hierarchy when it comes to receiving food from adults! This pup may darken as he ages, and there is an outward chance that his whole body will be a large white spot, which sometimes happens with domestic dogs and cats. We'll keep a close eye to see how its color evolves 🐶 Thanks to the expert researchers in Botswana for their insight! Dr Peter Apps Dr John Tico McNutt Dr Gabriele Cozzi Botswana Predator Conservation

[ Transcript ] “Since 1981, the United States has followed a policy, until the last year or so when we started rethinking it, that we rich countries that produce a lot of food should sell it to poor countries and relieve them of the burden of producing their own food, so, thank goodness, they can leap directly into the industrial era. It has not worked. It may have been good for some of my farmers in Arkansas, but it has not worked. It was a mistake. It was a mistake that I was a party to. I am not pointing the finger at anybody. I did that. I have to live every day with the consequences of the lost capacity to produce a rice crop in Haiti to feed those people, because of what I did. Nobody else.”

text: The Supreme Court on Monday restored Donald Trump to 2024 presidential primary ballots, rejecting state attempts to hold the Republican former president accountable for the Capitol riot. The justices ruled a day before the Super Tuesday primaries that states cannot invoke a post-Civil War constitutional provision to keep presidential candidates from appearing on ballots. That power resides with Congress, the court wrote in an unsigned opinion. The outcome ends efforts in Colorado, Illinois, Maine and elsewhere to kick Trump, the front-runner for his party's nomination, off the ballot because of his attempts to undo his loss in the 2020 election to Democrat Joe Biden, culminating in the Jan. 6, 2021, attack on the Capitol. text: Small Life Hack 🔥  It is part of the culture. Coffee shops are convenient for meetings, studying, meeting up, etc. A cup of coffee really can help get our day started and inspired to begin the day! If stopping by, or hanging out at a coffee shop is your thing,  one small hack you can do to keep a strong immune system is to bring your own coffee mug to coffee shops so that you mitigate your chances of absorbing micro plastics.  Also.. it’s a little less waste we are putting into the dump. Health and wellness comes, or lack there of, comes from consistent actions or inactions. You get to choose the direction the pendulum swings. I’ll be making this change, too. text: Boston Dynamics’ Robot Atlas shows off human-like skills. The Atlas robot can now run, jump, pick up, throw heavy objects and perform complex moves that may one day help humans in factories or on construction sites.  The video released titled “Atlas Gets a Grip” displays the Atlas robot picking up not only the tool bag but also a larger wooden plank to make it’s way up the stairs and jumping in between levels without loosing it’s balance. The Atlas finished off with an incredible complex 540-degree, multi-axis flip.  Unlike Boston Dynamics’ four-legged Spot robot, Atlas is not commercially available. The technology team hopes to eventually give robots the technological capabilities to “perform real, physical demanding jobs with hustle”.  #atlas #robots #technews #bostondynamics
